The Challenge
John, a clinical machine operator, struggles with the intricate and error-prone manual command-line operations of the histopathology machine. Navigating the complexities of block processing, monitoring, and maintaining consumables has become a significant challenge in
Problem Statement
The existing histopathology workflow faced by John involves a lack of user-friendly interface, real-time insights, and efficient monitoring. The absence of streamlined processes and visibility into block operations and consumables poses hurdles in ensuring accurate slide generation. The challenge is to design an intuitive HMI UX/UI that simplifies John's tasks, offers real-time progress tracking, and empowers him to efficiently manage consumables, ensuring precise and smooth processing of clinical blocks.

John Anderson

I rely on intuitive solutions to streamline tasks and ensure accurate outcomes.
Brief story
John, a dedicated clinical machine operator in New York, grapples with the complexities of manual command-line operations. Seeking simplicity, he embraces a user-friendly UI. With its introduction, he effortlessly launches the machine, tracks real-time progress, accesses live camera feeds, and receives alerts. This UI enhances his workflow, empowering him to manage consumables, assess slide quality, and complete each cycle confidently.
Goals
Streamline
Simplify
Ensure
Monitor
Frustrations
Complexity
Manual
Challenges
Uncertainty
User Scenario:

John starts his shift by reviewing the list of blocks to be processed and assessing available consumables.
He uses the intuitive UI to initiate the machine and monitor the progress of each block's operations.
Real-time status updates and progress bars allow him to stay informed about each block's stage.
John can easily view live camera feeds to visually monitor the machine's processes.
If any block is faulty or if there are processing issues, he receives clear alerts.
He appreciates the consumables status section, which provides real-time information about inventory levels.
After the cycle completes, John reviews the final slide output for each block on the UI.
He receives a pop-up message confirming processing completion and allowing him to unload the blocks.
John uses the UI to turn off the machine safely and concludes his tasks for the session.
User Needs and Goals in the UI/UX:
A clean and responsive interface that minimizes complexity.
User-friendly controls to initiate and manage processing cycles.
Real-time visibility into the status and progress of each block's operations.
Immediate alerts for faulty blocks or processing issues.
Access to live camera feeds for visual monitoring inside the machine.
Clear indication of consumables or inventory levels for planning.
Simplified confirmation mechanisms for important actions.
Ability to review the quality of final slide output quickly.
Streamlined navigation to facilitate efficient operations.

Challenges & Conclusion
1. Learning Curve:
Learning Curve: The transition to the new UI introduced a learning curve for John, requiring some time for him to become fully accustomed to the new layout and features.
2. Initial Compatibility Challenges:
Initial Compatibility Challenges: Ensuring compatibility across various devices and screen sizes presented challenges during the initial rollout, requiring adjustments to optimize the UI for a seamless experience.
In conclusion, the tailored UI/UX design for John, the dedicated clinical machine operator, not only addresses his challenges but transforms his entire workflow. By introducing a user-friendly interface, we've enabled John to navigate the complex histopathology operations effortlessly. Real-time insights, simplified monitoring, and intuitive controls have not only enhanced his efficiency but also empowered him to manage consumables and assess slide quality with confidence. This design solution bridges the gap between technology and John's expertise, resulting in a seamless and accurate histopathology process that contributes to accurate diagnoses and impactful research outcomes.
